05636nam a22007455i 9789048503872DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122005ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485038727 a10.1515/97890485038722doi  a(DE-B1597)518170  a(OCoLC)1088908801  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aPSY0000002bisacsh04a347.0671 aWagenaar, W. A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Popular Policeman and Other Cases :bPsychological Perspectives on Legal Evidence /cH. F. M. Crombag, W. A. Wagenaar. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (286 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- t1. Illegal Gambling or the Victory Travel Club -- t2. On Causal Reasoning or Death in the Warmoesstraat -- t3. Consumer Confusion or Potato Chips and Olive Oil -- t4. Fiction and Reality of 'the Average Individual' or the Case of Old Mr. Lane -- t5. Case Histories and Scientific Proof or the Case of JR -- t6. Not a Good Story or the Disappearance of Maddy and Vicky -- t7. Conflicting Scenarios or the Case of the Man Who Needed a Companion -- t8. Two Processes Obstructing the Accuracy of Long-Term Memory or the Case of the Stolen Mercedes -- t9. Confessions after Repeated Interrogation or the Putten Murder Case -- t10. Collaborative Storytelling or the Artist's Models and an Angry Neighbourhood -- t11. Allegation of Sexual Child Abuse in a Case of Disputed Visitation or Cindy's Story -- t12. Psychogenic Amnesia or the Case of the Amnesic Strangler -- t13. Obeying Reflexes or Death on the Climbing Wall -- t14. Visual Acuity or Shooting Mimi the Cat -- t15. Sexual Semiotics or the Case of the Popular Policeman -- tPostscript: Psychological Expertise and the Law -- tBibliography -- tName Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe role of psychologists, both in the courtroom and at the crime scene, is rapidly expanding. Surveying a wide range of international court cases, The Popular Policeman and Other Cases explores the critical-and often misunderstood-intersection of psychology and law. The authors, both expert psychologists with extensive experience in the courtroom, are quite familiar with the fundamental differences between the law and psychology as an empirical science. As well as dealing with well-known and controversial issues such as recovered memories or false confessions, The Popular Policeman and Other Cases examines a variety of less traditional criminal topics, including illegal gambling, trademark litigation, and the perils of risky courtship behavior. Each chapter reviews an actual case, appraises the relevant scientific research, and then demonstrates how psychological insights were introduced within the courtroom. The authors conclude by noting the outcome of each case-and how their research played a role in the decision. With its detailed investigation of the complex links between psychological research and its eventual application in the courtroom, The Popular Policeman and Other Cases fills a critical vacancy. It is virtually impossible for researchers to make significant progress within the field of law and psychology without experience as expert witnesses in actual trials. This casebook will be essential for their studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aElectronic books. -- local. 0aEvidence, Criminal -- Psychological aspects -- Cases. 0aForensic psychology -- Cases. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh1 aCrombag, H. F. M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067108i